movies_cols = ['movieId', 'title', 'genres']
movies_df = spark.read.option("delimiter", ",").option("header", True).csv('ml-32m/movies.csv', schema=StructType([
    StructField('movieId', IntegerType(), True),
    StructField('title', StringType(), True),
    StructField('genres', StringType(), True)
])).toDF(*movies_cols)

tags_cols = ['userId', 'movieId', 'tag', 'timestamp']
tags_df = spark.read.option("delimiter", ",").option("header", True).csv('ml-32m/tags.csv', schema=StructType([
    StructField('userId', IntegerType(), True),
    StructField('movieId', IntegerType(), True),
    StructField('tag', StringType(), True),
    StructField('timestamp', IntegerType(), True)
])).toDF(*tags_cols)

links_cols = ['movieId', 'imdbId', 'tmdbId']
links_df = spark.read.option("delimiter", ",").option("header", True).csv('ml-32m/links.csv', schema=StructType([
    StructField('movieId', IntegerType(), True),
    StructField('imdbId', IntegerType(), True),
    StructField('tmdbId', IntegerType(), True)
])).toDF(*links_cols)

Insight 1: Data is 99.8% sparse

In[11]:
# total combinations of users and movies
total_comb = ratings_df.select('userId').distinct().count() * movies_df.select('movieId').distinct().count()
print(f"Total possible user-movie combinations: {total_comb}")

rating_count = ratings_df.count()
print(f"Total ratings in dataset: {rating_count}")

sparsity = 1 - (rating_count / total_comb)
print(f"Sparsity of the ratings matrix: {sparsity:.6f}")

The dataset has 99.8% sparsity, meaning that most of the elements in user-movie matrix is empty.

In[13]:
cutoff_value = rating_count_per_user['rating_count'].quantile(0.90)
cutoff_log = np.log10(cutoff_value)

top_10_users = rating_count_per_user[rating_count_per_user['rating_count'] >= cutoff_value]
total_ratings = rating_count_per_user['rating_count'].sum()
top_10_contribution = top_10_users['rating_count'].sum()
contribution_pct = (top_10_contribution / total_ratings) * 100

ax = sns.histplot(np.log10(rating_count_per_user['rating_count']), bins=50, kde=False)
y_bottom, y_top = ax.get_ylim()
x_left, x_right = ax.get_xlim()
ax.axvline(x=cutoff_log, color='r', linestyle='--', linewidth=2)
midpoint_x = cutoff_log + (x_right - cutoff_log) / 2
plt.fill_betweenx([0, ax.get_ylim()[1]], cutoff_log, ax.get_xlim()[1], color='red', alpha=0.2)
plt.text(x=midpoint_x, y=y_top * 0.2, s='Top 10%', fontsize=12, color='darkred', ha='center', bbox=dict(facecolor='white', alpha=0.5, edgecolor='none'))
plt.title(f'Distribution of Rating Counts per User (Log Transformed)\n[Insight: Top 10% users contribute {contribution_pct:.2f}% of the ratings]')
plt.xlabel('Log(Rating Count) (Base 10)')
plt.ylabel('Number of Users')
plt.show();
In[14]:
# gini coefficient to measure inequality in ratings distribution among users

cumulative_ratings = rating_count_per_user['rating_count'].sort_values().cumsum()
cumulative_ratings_pct = cumulative_ratings / cumulative_ratings.iloc[-1]
cumulative_users_pct = np.arange(1, len(rating_count_per_user) + 1) / len(rating_count_per_user)
gini_coefficient = (0.5 - np.trapezoid(cumulative_ratings_pct, cumulative_users_pct)) / 0.5

print(f"Gini Coefficient of Ratings Distribution among Users: {gini_coefficient*100:.2f}%")

sns.lineplot(x=cumulative_users_pct, y=cumulative_ratings_pct)
sns.lineplot(x=[0,1], y=[0,1], color='red', linestyle='--')
plt.fill_between(cumulative_users_pct, cumulative_ratings_pct, color='skyblue', alpha=0.4)
plt.title('Lorenz Curve of Ratings Distribution among Users')
plt.xlabel('Cumulative % of Users')
plt.ylabel('Cumulative % of Ratings')
plt.show();

Gini Coefficient of Ratings Distribution among Users: 59.37%

A high gini coefficient and Lorenz curve that bows very further from the red dotted lines shows inequality in rating count between users.

rating_count_per_movie = rating_count_per_movie.sort_values(by='rating_count', ascending=False).reset_index(drop=True)
nonpopular_movies_idx = rating_count_per_movie[rating_count_per_movie['rating_count'] <= 10].index
nonpopular_movies_pct = (len(nonpopular_movies_idx) / len(rating_count_per_movie)) * 100
sorted_counts = rating_count_per_movie['rating_count'].sort_values(ascending=False).values
x_rank = np.arange(len(sorted_counts))

plt.loglog(x_rank[:nonpopular_movies_idx[0]+1], sorted_counts[:nonpopular_movies_idx[0]+1], color='tab:blue')
plt.plot(nonpopular_movies_idx[0], 10, 'o', color='red')
plt.loglog(x_rank[nonpopular_movies_idx[0]:], sorted_counts[nonpopular_movies_idx[0]:], color='tab:red', label='Movies with <=10 ratings')
plt.text(x=nonpopular_movies_idx[0], y=15, s=f"{nonpopular_movies_pct:.2f}% of movies have 10 or fewer ratings", fontsize=10, color='darkred', ha='center', bbox=dict(facecolor='white', alpha=0.5, edgecolor='none'))
plt.title("Log-Log Scale of Movie Rank vs Rating Counts")

plt.xlabel("Movie Rank (Log)")
plt.ylabel("Number of Ratings (Log)")
plt.grid(True, which="both", ls="--")

plt.show()

From this graph, we can see that large count of ratings comes from only a small percentage of the whole movies, and 63.85% of movies have 10 or fewer ratings.

avg_rating_per_user_per_year = rating_per_user_per_year.groupby('year')[['avg_rating', 'count']].agg({'avg_rating':'mean', 'count':'sum'}).reset_index()

axes[0].set_ylabel('Average Rating per User')
axes[1].set_title('Count of Rating per Year')
axes[1].set_xlabel('Year')
axes[1].set_xticks(avg_rating_per_user_per_year['year'].unique())
axes[1].tick_params(axis='x', rotation=45)
axes[1].set_ylabel('Count of Rating')

axes[0].grid(True, which="both", ls="--")
axes[1].grid(True, which="both", ls="--")
plt.tight_layout();
plt.show();

The data shows a noticeable decline in average ratings from 1999 to 2004, followed by a steady recovery and increase from 2004 through 2023. While the volume of ratings remains volatile year-over-year, it is notable that the rating counts in the 1990s are comparable to those in the 2010s, indicating that user activity levels have remained robust over the decades.

Movies released in the 2000s benefited from higher popularity on MovieLens (high rating counts) largely because the platform launched in 1997. Movies from the 1800s to the 1990s were likely just as popular with audiences at the time, but their initial engagement was never recorded because MovieLens did not exist yet. Interestingly, movies released around 1995 have the highest volume of ratings in the entire dataset, surpassing even the 2010s which had a higher total number of movie releases.

In[65]:
year_mapping = {"1800 - 1899": range(1800, 1899),
                "1900s": range(1900, 1910),
                "1910s": range(1910, 1920),
                "1920s": range(1920, 1930),
                "1930s": range(1930, 1940),
                "1940s": range(1940, 1950),
                "1950s": range(1950, 1960),
                "1960s": range(1960, 1970),
                "1970s": range(1970, 1980),
                "1980s": range(1980, 1990),
                "1990s": range(1990, 2000),
                "2000s": range(2000, 2010),
                "2010s": range(2010, 2020),
                "2020s": range(2020, 2030)}

release_rated_year['releaseYearGroup'] = release_rated_year['releaseYear'].apply(lambda x: next((k for k, v in year_mapping.items() if x in v), 'Unknown'))
release_rated_year['yearGroup'] = release_rated_year['year'].apply(lambda x: next((k for k, v in year_mapping.items() if x in v), 'Unknown'))
In[71]:
sns.heatmap(release_rated_year.pivot_table(index='releaseYearGroup', columns='yearGroup', values='count_rating', aggfunc='sum').fillna(0), cmap='YlGnBu')
plt.xlabel('Rated Year')
plt.ylabel('Release Year')
plt.title('Ratings Count by Release Year and Rated Year')
plt.tight_layout();

In the 2000s, the majority of ratings were given to movies released in the 1990s. This suggests a distinct pattern where users tend to watch and rate films released roughly a decade earlier. This trend persisted into the 2010s; despite the high volume of new releases shown in the previous graph, users still rated 2000s movies more frequently. Movies released two decades prior also maintained some popularity, though not as strongly as those from the preceding decade.

        y=rating_per_genre['avg_rating'].iloc[i] + 0.01,
        s=rating_per_genre['genre'].iloc[i], 
        fontdict=dict(color='black', size=8)
    )
plt.title('Average Rating vs. Number of Ratings per Genre')
plt.xlabel('Number of Ratings')
plt.ylabel('Average Rating')
plt.tight_layout();
plt.show();

While unpopular (low rating volume) genres show significant variance in quality, the top three highest-rated genres such as Film-Noir, War, and Documentary are all niche categories. In contrast, the top three most popular genres (Drama, Comedy, and Action) maintain relatively high ratings but lack the consistent excellence found in these niche categories. This suggests a 'Selection Bias' where niche genres are primarily rated by dedicated enthusiasts, whereas popular genres attract a broader, more critical audience.
